item.description:
duplicate: <p>
It should be possible to customize login page by hooking into <code>login_enqueue_scripts</code> action (and using <code>!important</code> in style definitions if necessary):
</p>
<pre class="wiki">function customize_my_login_page() {
	wp_enqueue_style('my-login-style', '.../my-login-style.css');
	wp_print_styles();
}
add_action('login_enqueue_scripts', 'customize_my_login_page');
</pre><p>
<code>wp_print_styles()</code> needs to be added in this case, since it's not called automatically for <code>login_head</code>. Related discussion: <a class="reopened ticket" href="http://core.trac.wordpress.org/ticket/17916#comment:12" title="Comment 12 for #17916: defect (bug): Enqueued styles are only printed on login_footer in wp-login.php (reopened)">ticket:17916:12</a>.
</p>
<p>
Closing as a duplicate of <a class="closed ticket" href="http://core.trac.wordpress.org/ticket/19130" title="#19130: defect (bug): current wp-login.php call to wp_admin_css() bypasses its own filter (closed: invalid)">#19130</a>.
</p>
